benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/versions - Retrieve a list of catalog versions

covered: Valid Request: Multiple scenarios (TC01, TC02, TC14) validate successful retrieval with and without accountId and compatibility with older clients.
Empty Response: TC03 and TC13 verify behavior when no catalog versions exist (empty JSON array, no stack trace).

Query Parameters: Extensive coverage — valid accountId (TC02, TC18), non-existent accountId (TC04), invalid formats (TC05, TC16, TC17), unsupported extra params ignored (TC09), and SQL injection attempt (TC12).
Authorization: Authentication-related failures are covered (TC06 missing token, TC07 invalid/expired token returning 401).
Response Format & Validation: Content-type checks and JSON array-of-strings are asserted (TC01, TC20); ISO 8601 validation is checked in multiple scenarios.
Error Handling: General error conditions covered — malformed JSON/server error (TC19 -> 500), service unavailable (TC08 -> 503), invalid input -> 400 (TC05, TC16, TC17, TC12).
Performance & Scalability: Large payload/performance testing (TC10), concurrency testing (TC15), and slow downstream dependency/timeout handling (TC11) are present.
Security: SQL injection attempt is tested (TC12) and tests assert no sensitive information leakage.
Edge Cases: Mixed-case UUID handling (TC18), empty accountId param (TC16), leading/trailing spaces (TC17) covered.
Accessibility / Machine-readable: TC20 asserts API returns machine-readable JSON (no HTML).
gaps: Pagination: No scenarios test pagination semantics (limit/offset/page tokens), response size controls, or partial result behavior for very large datasets.
Caching Behavior: No tests verify caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional requests (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since).
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests exercise rate-limiting behavior (429 responses) or client throttling under high request rates; concurrency tests exist but not rate-limit tests.

Authorization granularity (403): Tests cover unauthenticated (401) but do not cover forbidden/authorization scenarios (403) for users authenticated but not authorized to view tenant-specific catalogs.
Pagination performance & streaming: While TC10 checks 10k items, there is no validation of memory/streaming behavior or server-side pagination limits/exceptions for huge payloads.

Content Negotiation & Headers: No tests for Accept header handling or behavior when client requests non-JSON (e.g., Accept: text/html) or when response includes relevant headers (Content-Length, Content-Encoding).
Ordering / Deduplication / Consistency: No tests assert ordering of returned dates, uniqueness, or whether returned versions are stable across repeated requests (idempotency/consistency).
Error semantics coverage: While some error cases exist, there are no tests for other client errors (e.g., 422 Unprocessable Entity if applicable) or for malformed query strings beyond simple cases.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: implement scenarios for limit/offset or page tokens, verify total counts, boundaries (first/last page), and behavior when requesting pages beyond available data.
Add caching tests: verify presence and correctness of ETag/Cache-Control/Last-Modified headers, and test conditional GETs using If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since to confirm 304 behavior.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate high request rates to validate 429 responses, Retry-After headers, and graceful handling of throttling.

Add authorization granularity tests: include scenarios where an authenticated user lacks permission to view tenant data and should receive 403 Forbidden, and tests for tenant isolation/authorization rules.
Add content-negotiation and header validation tests: verify Accept header behavior, Content-Length/Encoding correctness, and behavior for non-JSON Accept values.

Add ordering/consistency tests: assert whether returned effective dates are ordered (e.g., ascending/descending), that duplicates are handled appropriately, and that results are consistent across repeated calls.
Expand performance endurance tests: beyond a single 10k item test, include streaming/memory usage checks, and server behavior for extremely large payloads or sudden spikes.

Clarify and test error taxonomy: add tests for other potential error codes relevant to the API implementation (e.g., 422 if semantics apply) and ensure error responses do not leak stack traces or sensitive info beyond TC19/TC13 coverage.
